00:10:25.200 --> 00:10:29.039
What has the progression been like for you,

00:10:29.039 --> 00:10:33.840
like moving from an analyst to data scientist to leading a data science team?

00:10:35.599 --> 00:10:40.239
The first thing is that because when I work as an analyst, most of my job is kind of ad hoc

00:10:40.239 --> 00:10:46.159
analysis. So I put data, I build reports, I do some other analysis and present my results for

00:10:46.159 --> 00:10:51.520
the leadership team. However, I later found that so instead of just doing something ad hoc, I want

00:10:51.599 --> 00:10:58.880
to do something a kind of more systematic. Again, I'm always, because my secondary degree was in

00:10:58.880 --> 00:11:05.039
operations research as basically math modeling. So I still want to build models for all the

00:11:05.039 --> 00:11:12.239
analytical jobs. And because my first job was for a health care company. So that time I want to say,

00:11:12.239 --> 00:11:18.719
okay, so can we use all the data to predict the behavior of patients? And I start, I built my

00:11:19.039 --> 00:11:23.840
first predict model during that time. And after that, I believe that this is what I want to do.

00:11:24.640 --> 00:11:30.000
So that's why I want to pivot to, and it's a little, it's a small pivoting from analyst to

00:11:30.000 --> 00:11:36.000
data scientist. And after that, because I changed to, I switched to a financial service company.

00:11:36.000 --> 00:11:41.119
So I'll come in doing subprime loans, and then which is subprime auto lender. Because if you

00:11:41.119 --> 00:11:45.280
want to buy a car, you'll go to a dealership. And if you cannot pay cash, you need to

00:11:45.280 --> 00:11:52.239
apply for a car loan. And because if your credit score is not that well, for our definition,

00:11:52.239 --> 00:11:57.919
subprime means that people with credit score less than 620. And for that customer segment,

00:11:57.919 --> 00:12:02.719
there are a lot of risk there. So we need, you need to build a lot of predict models to predict

00:12:02.719 --> 00:12:08.719
the risk and then price it to manage the price, manage how we service the law, how we originate

00:12:08.880 --> 00:12:14.640
the law. So this is why our entire subprime lending business is driven by data science.

00:12:15.200 --> 00:12:22.719
And because of this, I feel that, okay, I had my knowledge and my desire, my interest plays a super

00:12:22.719 --> 00:12:28.080
important role for the business. So that's why, okay, this is the industry I like. And I started

00:12:28.080 --> 00:12:33.520
as a data scientist and gradually I feel, okay, it's not just about modeling. So you can just

00:12:33.520 --> 00:12:38.799
say they are building model coding every day, but this is the most basic work. So if you want to do

00:12:38.799 --> 00:12:43.280
it really well, you'll need to understand the business part. You need to understand, okay,

00:12:43.280 --> 00:12:49.359
so what problem the business is facing and how can you formulate a business problem into a data

00:12:49.359 --> 00:12:56.559
science problem? And then build a model is the, I would say, the simplest part. And with this,

00:12:57.520 --> 00:13:03.679
I kind of, I actually started to, I mean, spend my time to collaborate with all the other teams

00:13:03.679 --> 00:13:09.280
in the company, try to understand their work, their work, okay. How is the sales, how is the

00:13:09.280 --> 00:13:14.559
sales team working? How is the marketing team working? How is the local origination teams working?

00:13:14.559 --> 00:13:19.599
And by gradually, because I have more and more understanding of the business, I kind of gradually

00:13:19.840 --> 00:13:24.880
And by gradually, because I have more and more understanding of the business, I kind of gradually

00:13:24.880 --> 00:13:32.960
move up in the queer hierarchy, I'll call it. And after I become a senior manager of data science,

00:13:32.960 --> 00:13:39.679
I feel that, okay, so my data science knowledge is not enough. So if you go to a higher level,

00:13:39.679 --> 00:13:44.000
it's not about coding, it's not about data science. You'll need, suddenly you'll need some

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:48.159
hard skills from other areas. For example, you need to understand accounting, you need to

00:13:48.159 --> 00:13:52.320
understand finance, you need to understand marketing. And for all of these, okay, I think,

00:13:52.320 --> 00:13:57.440
okay, I need to learn something, probably. Of course, ideally, you can also outsource these

00:13:57.440 --> 00:14:02.159
skills, okay, because if you are a leader, you need some accounting, higher accounting. You need

00:14:02.159 --> 00:14:06.320
some financial knowledge, hire a financial manager or financial analyst. And if you need marketing,

00:14:06.320 --> 00:14:11.359
hire a marketing manager. But these hard skills, you can outsource. But there are also another part

00:14:11.359 --> 00:14:16.159
of probably what I call them soft skills. You can only do it by yourself. For example, like,

00:14:16.159 --> 00:14:20.960
how to build a production, productive team. Like how to, for example, how to do business

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:26.880
negotiations. All these skills, you cannot outsource them to other people. And other people

00:14:26.880 --> 00:14:31.280
help you do it. You need to do it yourself. And that's why I decided, okay, I need to go back to

00:14:31.280 --> 00:14:34.960
school. I need to pursue an EMBA program. Probably this is the best time for me.

00:14:36.320 --> 00:14:40.799
And I started a program last year at Cornell University. And later, if you're interested,

00:14:40.799 --> 00:14:47.760
I can explain why I think that this program fits a lot of people in the audience for a while

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:55.440
because of its format and because of its goal. And so, but right now, Rachel, I can put the mic

00:14:55.440 --> 00:15:03.679
go back to you. Yeah, absolutely. And I know we shared in the chat, if you want to ask questions

00:15:03.679 --> 00:15:08.159
anonymously, you can use Slido. But feel free to just raise your hand here if you want to jump in

00:15:08.159 --> 00:15:14.880
the conversation too. But you, I love the way that you explained working with different parts

00:15:14.880 --> 00:15:20.799
of the business to actually understand the business problems. And I was wondering what,

00:15:20.799 --> 00:15:26.159
like, what that process looks like for you of building relationships with different people

00:15:26.159 --> 00:15:31.359
across the business? Is it like joining some of their meetings? Like, how do you go about that?

00:15:32.080 --> 00:15:37.679
Actually, it all started with networking. Because I know a lot of, because I work with

00:15:37.679 --> 00:15:43.280
very analytical, I would say, very nerdy team. So a lot of people, they are, okay, I just want

00:15:43.280 --> 00:15:50.159
to code. I just want to build a fantastic model. I do not want to spend too much time to network

00:15:50.159 --> 00:15:56.719
with people from other business lines. But actually, this is probably, I would say,

00:15:56.880 --> 00:16:01.280
know the right attitude. Because if you want to collaborate with other people,

00:16:01.280 --> 00:16:06.880
first, you need to get to know them. You need to understand how their business is. And yeah,

00:16:06.880 --> 00:16:11.119
in other words, probably most essential, you need to become their friends. So usually,

00:16:11.119 --> 00:16:16.559
I reach out to them and say, okay, do a self introduction. And this is what I do. This is

00:16:16.559 --> 00:16:21.119
what my team can do. So let us go out for lunch. Let us go out for, let us grab a cup of coffee.

00:16:21.119 --> 00:16:25.440
Let us talk about for 15 minutes. Let us see what kind of business, what kind of difficulties you

00:16:25.440 --> 00:16:30.479
are having now in your business. If you are a sales team, are you worrying about how to increase

00:16:30.479 --> 00:16:36.159
the volume of sales? If you are a loan originations team, are you worried about how to increase the

00:16:36.159 --> 00:16:41.280
capital rate? And then let us talk about that. Then I will see, okay, how can I connect my

00:16:41.280 --> 00:16:46.799
data science knowledge with the problem you are facing now? See whether I can build a model to

00:16:48.320 --> 00:16:52.559
help you solve the problem you have. Usually, the collaboration starts with this.

00:16:53.359 --> 00:16:58.559
And when you build a model for them, how do you share that with them?

00:17:00.159 --> 00:17:05.439
I would say that probably, again, that is a very important part because our data scientist has to

00:17:05.439 --> 00:17:11.199
be a very good storyteller. It is easy to build a model today because we have auto ML, we have

00:17:11.760 --> 00:17:16.160
wire-array automatic pipelines. Basically, we can talk about that later. So we design our model

00:17:16.880 --> 00:17:22.160
in a pipeline, like a streamline or something like that. So basically, even if you have no

00:17:22.160 --> 00:17:26.239
knowledge of data science, you will just change some hyperparameters and then you will click a

00:17:26.239 --> 00:17:33.040
button, of course in RStudio, and after two hours or two days, that is on the side of your data set,

00:17:33.040 --> 00:17:38.719
you can get a bunch of models. And a lot of time, mostly, this model performs well.

00:17:39.359 --> 00:17:43.199
But this is only the beginning. And then the difficult part is that you need to sell these

00:17:43.199 --> 00:17:48.160
models, like your own product. You need to let the business owners, stakeholders,

00:17:48.959 --> 00:17:55.199
buy this model. You can build a very good model mirroring dealer risk. However, you need to be

00:17:55.199 --> 00:18:01.760
able to let your dealer sales managers understand this model. And they should be able to explain

00:18:01.760 --> 00:18:08.640
this to the dealers. I cannot reach out to every dealer and say, OK, this is a large GBM model,

00:18:08.880 --> 00:18:14.239
that builds mirroring risk. They won't buy it. No, we don't want to hear about it at all.

00:18:15.599 --> 00:18:24.560
So the model needs to be transparent, needs to be very explainable. And to do that,

00:18:24.560 --> 00:18:30.880
usually, my approach starts from the easiest one. So usually, if we build a new model,

00:18:30.880 --> 00:18:35.520
for example, either to help for the sales team or mirror the risk of dealers,

00:18:36.079 --> 00:18:41.119
usually, we start with a simple logistic regression model. Because, frankly, everybody

00:18:41.680 --> 00:18:45.920
understands a little bit about logistic regression, or pretends that they understand

00:18:45.920 --> 00:18:51.439
logistic regression. So usually, if you present a logistic regression model, there won't be a

00:18:51.439 --> 00:18:56.000
lot of pushback. You'll say, OK, I understand that. Just tell me about all the variables.

00:18:56.000 --> 00:19:00.079
And then if the directions of the variables make sense, we'll buy it. And we can explain that to

00:19:01.040 --> 00:19:09.040
the other users. And after that, when you build some relationship or trust with your

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:15.760
customers, all the users of these models, then later, you can gradually push things forward.

00:19:15.760 --> 00:19:21.359
I'll say, OK, so from the next step, we know some machine learning algorithms. The models

00:19:21.359 --> 00:19:27.119
we build using these algorithms perform better. They are more predictive. And they are explainable.

00:19:27.119 --> 00:19:33.599
I can try to show that, show you how to explain that. And they are 100% compliant,

00:19:33.599 --> 00:19:38.719
because we are in a highly regulated industry. So everything we build, we are usually audited by

00:19:39.359 --> 00:19:43.760
people from the government annually, every year. They will say, OK, they will check all the models

00:19:43.760 --> 00:19:48.959
we build, say whether this is discriminatory, whether all the models we use are compliant,

00:19:48.959 --> 00:19:54.319
these kind of things. And we are sure that, OK, the model is fully compliant, is fully transparent,

00:19:54.319 --> 00:20:01.520
and is accepted by, I won't say accepted by the entire industry, but is accepted by a lot of

00:20:01.520 --> 00:20:06.239
players in the industry. So because we are not the biggest company in the industry, we are probably

00:20:06.239 --> 00:20:12.880
