And so because the impact hasn't reached out to our business right now, just because

00:59:39.760 --> 00:59:44.080
our customers are different from the people being impacted right now.

00:59:46.000 --> 00:59:46.719
Thank you, Yu.

00:59:48.560 --> 00:59:54.800
Thank you. Okay, one last question that I see I had missed over on Slido. The question was,

00:59:55.600 --> 01:00:03.360
do you use R, Python, SAS, or Excel, VBA? And in what mix? Are there legacy systems in your

01:00:03.360 --> 01:00:07.360
industry that you must deal with? When I joined the company,

01:00:07.360 --> 01:00:13.600
Accelerator Finance, the whole modeling process was in SAS. At that time, I know almost nothing

01:00:13.600 --> 01:00:20.080
about SAS. So I just fake it. So I'm like, okay, I know, I know SAS. But at that time, I know R a

01:00:20.080 --> 01:00:25.919
lot. So fortunately, at that time, we were transitioning from SAS to R. And then I started

01:00:25.919 --> 01:00:32.800
to build our whole pipeline in R. And then right now, I would say that our model pipeline is

01:00:32.800 --> 01:00:39.679
10 minutes, I would say it's 95% in R. Again, in the future, R is very nice. I like R a lot.

01:00:39.679 --> 01:00:44.159
But in the future, from the implementation perspective, Python is more convenient.

01:00:44.159 --> 01:00:47.360
And again, you will see a lot of machine learning papers, algorithms.

01:00:47.919 --> 01:00:53.280
When the author publishes a paper, they just build a Python library and then show it in GitHub.

01:00:53.919 --> 01:00:58.000
I reach out to them, okay, can you write an R version? They said, no, thanks.

01:00:58.639 --> 01:01:03.280
So right now, I want our people in my team to be bilingual.

01:01:03.280 --> 01:01:07.360
So we can code in R, we can code in SAS. We can code in R, we can code in Python.

01:01:07.360 --> 01:01:13.040
For SAS, we still use it for reporting perspective to generate some reports. But that's it.

01:01:13.919 --> 01:01:19.120
For Excel, VBA, we use it a little bit to build some, because for example,

01:01:20.800 --> 01:01:23.840
if you want to do ad hoc analysis, Excel is very convenient.

01:01:23.840 --> 01:01:28.080
And sometimes, if you want to build a summary report, kind of model summary,

01:01:28.080 --> 01:01:32.239
model documentation, we have some VBA in Excel to generate some figures.

01:01:35.520 --> 01:01:41.199
Great. Thank you so much, Yu. I know we have just crossed over the top of the hour here.

